From the experimental results, it can be observed that the desalination rate and the production rate of HCl and LiOH appear to be independent of the compartment length. In both cases, the final concentrations of HCl (acid chamber) and LiOH (basic chamber) solutions were 0.78 M and 1 M, respectively. However, the initial cell voltage increased from 11.5 V to 16.85 V when the cell length increased. As expected, higher distance between the electrodes increases the electrical resistance of the cell, resulting in higher energy consumption [33]. As can be seen from Fig. 10
                           , the SEC to produce HCl and LiOH decreased from 13.4 kWh·kg−1 HCl to 8.3 kWh·kg−1 HCl and 22.4 kWh·kg−1 LiOH to 13.7 kWh·kg−1 LiOH when the compartment length is reduced from 16 cm to 8 cm. The CE referred to the Cl− ions and Li+ transportation was similar in both cases (79.6 % in ED1 and 76.85 % in ED4), due to the recovery ratio of Cl− and Li+ was also identical (Table 3
                           ).
